Script: 1-hello_you
#!/bin/bash
echo "hello $USER"

Explanation:
First line: #!/bin/bash - Shebang specifying Bash interpreter

Second line: echo "hello $USER" - Prints "hello" followed by the value of the USER environment variable

How it works:
$USER is a reserved environment variable (covered in Package 3) that contains the current username

When the script runs, $USER undergoes parameter expansion (covered in Package 1) and is replaced with the actual username

The echo command then outputs the complete string

Demonstration:
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ id
uid=1000(julien) gid=1000(julien) groups=1000(julien),4(adm),24(cdrom),27(sudo),30(dip),46(plugdev),113(lpadmin),128(sambashare)
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ ./1-hello_you 
hello julien

Key concepts demonstrated:
Reserved variables (USER variable)

Parameter expansion ($USER expands to the username)

Environment variables (variables available in all shells)

This script will work in your sandbox environment and print "hello 6dfa82e5d5e7" since that's the username in your provided credentials.

